The scan only emitted the accessibility finding here, but `Card.tsx` exhibits all three frontend agent-risks named in the prompt. The file is:

```tsx
<div
  style={{ width: 800, background: "#ff00aa", color: "#0a0a0a" }}
  onClick={() => console.log("clicked")}
>
  {children}
</div>
```

## Proposed refactor

```tsx
type CardProps = {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  onActivate: () => void;
  label: string;
};

export function Card({ children, onActivate, label }: CardProps) {
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      onClick={onActivate}
      aria-label={label}
      className="w-full max-w-3xl bg-accent text-foreground"
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Each change → finding it kills

1. **`background: "#ff00aa"`, `color: "#0a0a0a"` → `bg-accent text-foreground` (Tailwind tokens)**
   Ties to **`design_token_escape`**. Inline hex literals bypass the design system, so a theme change (dark mode, brand reskin, accessibility palette swap) silently misses this component — that's the exact "multiple sources of truth" agent-risk the detector flags. Routing through token classes restores one source of truth.

2. **`<div onClick>` → `<button type="button" onClick aria-label>`**
   Ties to **`accessible_interaction_risk`** (the finding actually in the scan). The native button gives you keyboard focus, Enter/Space activation, the implicit `role="button"`, and a screen-reader-visible name — all four requirements in the detector's `suggested_actions.switch_to_button_or_add_aria`. `type="button"` is also needed so the element doesn't accidentally submit a parent form.

3. **`width: 800` → `w-full max-w-3xl`**
   Ties to **`responsive_fragility`**. A fixed 800px width breaks below ~820px viewports and inside narrower flex/grid parents — an agent dropping this card into a sidebar or mobile layout has no signal that it will overflow. `w-full max-w-3xl` keeps the visual cap (≈768px) while letting the container collapse responsively.

## Things I deliberately did *not* do

- I didn't keep `console.log("clicked")`. The handler should be passed in (`onActivate`) so the component is testable and side-effect-free — that's the same `direct side effects in domain code` axis as the testability detectors, just upstream.
- I didn't add `role="button"` + `tabIndex={0}` to the `<div>`. The detector lists that as an acceptable rescue, but it's strictly worse than a real `<button>`: you'd still need to wire Enter/Space handlers manually, and you'd be re-implementing what the platform gives you for free. Use the rescue only when the element genuinely can't be a button (e.g., it wraps an `<a>`).
